lationship to Islamic philosophers such as Ibn Sina (Avicenna) and Mulla Sadra. This study examines the contexts and approaches to Kant’s reception in Iran and shows how Kant’s thought has maintained a solid place in Iranian philosophical discourse.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aPhilosophyzIranxHistory. 4aIran. 4aIslamische Philosophie. 4aKant research Islamic philosophy. 4aKantforschung. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2014z9783110370393oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831103912130 cprintz978311036375340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311036482840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110364828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110364828.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-DPHb2014